dulcior, ‘more pleasing.’ So of the charm of Herodotus, Cicero in the Hor- tensius, ‘ quid enim aut Herodoto dulcius aut Thucydide graviusss’: cp. Quint. x· 1, 73, and note. Andresen quotes Cic. Or. ξ 32, of Xenophon's style, ‘ melle dulcior sed a forensi strepitu remotissimus.’

12. magis elaboratus. So Seneca, Controv. ii. 12, 8 Latini utique sermonis observator diligentissimus. Quintilian's judgment of Corvinus may be cited: At Messalla nitidus et candidus et quodam modo praeferens in dicendo nobilitatem suam, viribus minor (x. 1, 113). In the Brutus (ξ 246) Cicero says of him, M. Mes- salla minor natu quam nos, nullo modo inops, sed non nimis ornatus genere ver· borum: he also praises his industry, cp. Epist. ad Brut. i. 15, 1. Elaboratus, more usually of an author's style than of the author himself: e. g. Quint. ix. 4, 1.

probasse. The frequent use of the infinitive after such adjectives as contentus (and also after verbs) is a characteristic of the Silver Age. Other examples of this construction with contentus will be found in 23. 6 and 26. 27. It seems to have been adopted from the usage of poetry (e. g. Ovid, Metam. i. 461), and is very common in Quintilian—For the perf. infin. of a completed action, cp. Agr. iii. 18: xliv. 17.
